{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/how-to-run-jupyter-notebook-on-docker-7c9748ed209f", "time": 1683015244.9903219, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/how-to-run-jupyter-notebook-on-docker-7c9748ed209f/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "How to Run Jupyter Notebook on Docker | by Shinichi Okada | Towards Data Science", "h1": "How to Run Jupyter Notebook on Docker", "description": "You just use a Docker container! In this article, you will learn how to run Jupyter on Docker."}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.docker.com/why-docker", "anchor_text": "Developing with Docker", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop", "anchor_text": "Docker Desktop", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://docs.docker.com/docker-for-mac/#file-sharing", "anchor_text": "Mac", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://docs.docker.com/docker-for-windows/", "anchor_text": "Windows", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://github.com/jupyter/docker-stacks", "anchor_text": "Jupyter Docker Stacks", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "https://jupyter-docker-stacks.readthedocs.io/en/latest/using/selecting.html", "anchor_text": "different Docker images", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://hub.docker.com/r/jupyter/minimal-notebook/tags/", "anchor_text": "jupiter/minimal", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://hub.docker.com/r/jupyter/base-notebook", "anchor_text": "jupyter/base-notebook", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://docs.docker.com/engine/reference/run/#clean-up---rm", "anchor_text": "--rm", "paragraph_index": 32}, {"url": "https://hub.docker.com/", "anchor_text": "hub.docker", "paragraph_index": 45}, {"url": "https://hub.docker.com/r/jupyter/scipy-notebook", "anchor_text": "jupyter/scipy-notebook", "paragraph_index": 46}, {"url": "https://hub.docker.com/r/jupyter/tensorflow-notebook", "anchor_text": "jupyter/tensorfolow-notebook", "paragraph_index": 46}, {"url": "https://jupyter-docker-stacks.readthedocs.io/en/latest/using/selecting.html", "anchor_text": "these", "paragraph_index": 46}, {"url": "https://hub.docker.com/search?q=jupyter&type=image", "anchor_text": "links", "paragraph_index": 46}, {"url": "https://blog.codewithshin.com/membership", "anchor_text": "becoming a member", "paragraph_index": 48}], "all_paragraphs": ["Docker simplifies and accelerates your workflow, while giving developers the freedom to innovate with their choice of tools, application stacks, and deployment environments for each project. \u2014 from Developing with Docker", "Docker provides a contained environment for your development. By using Docker, you may not need to install pyenv/pipenv/virtualenv or any programming languages on your computer. You just use a Docker container! In this article, you will learn how to run Jupyter on Docker.", "The first command above will run the Jupyter minimal-notebook connecting the local directory to a Docker container.The second command is the same as the first one. Only the difference is running the Jupyter Scipy-notebook.", "Install Docker Desktop and when you start Docker you will see an icon in the menu bar.", "The Docker Preferences menu allows you to configure your Docker settings such as installation, updates, version channels, Docker Hub login, and more. Open Preferences and go to Resources to change CPUs, Memory, and other setups. By default, Docker Desktop is set to use half the number of processors available on the host machine.", "You can read more details on this page for Mac, and Windows.", "In your terminal run docker and you will see all commands:", "Docker groups the commands logically into management commands. Here are the top-level commands.", "You can get more information about Management Commands using --help.", "Jupyter Docker Stacks are a set of ready-to-run Docker images containing Jupyter applications and interactive computing tools.", "Official Jupyter created different Docker images and we are going to use jupiter/minimal to learn how to use Docker. The image is based on jupyter/base-notebook and it has command line tools, TeX Live, git, emacs, vi, jed, and more.", "Around the end of the outputs, you can find the URL with a token. You use cmd+click to open the URL on a browser.", "Open another terminal tab and check the container-id number.", "It is a bit hard to read the above output. Let\u2019s create a format.Add the following to your ~/.zshrc or ~/.bash_profile.", "And you can use it by adding it to the--format option for docker:", "You can use it with or without = sign as you see above.", "docker exec runs a command in a running container. The -i option allows us to use it interactively and the -t allocates a pseudo-TTY. We use /bin/bash to run a bash shell.", "The cb8b is the first 4 letters of my container. You have a different container id.", "You can find more information by using docker exec --help.", "Once you are in the container, you can run normal bash commands.", "Let\u2019s check the container Python and pip versions:", "This image has ipython and conda as well. Let\u2019s check them:", "You can find what Python packages are installed:", "Pandas, numpy, etc are not installed. You can install them using pip install pandas numpy:", "You can exit the bash using exit.CTRL-C exits a running container.", "You can stop a container using docker container stop <container-id>:", "You can find all the containers including inactive containers:", "You can remove an image using docker rmi <image-id>.", "-f force to remove a running container without stopping a container.", "If you want to remove all images at once:", "-a allows us to remove all images and -q shows numeric IDs after the removal.", "You can use remove all containers in the same way:", "Using --rmYou can run a container with --rm to automatically clean up the container when exit the container.", "You don\u2019t need to run docker ps -a and docker rm <image-id> after exiting your container.", "You can combine the option with -it.", "When you run this command, you can use the bash in the container and when you exit, it will clean up the container.", "Docker volumes are directories (or files) that are outside of the default Docker file system and exist as normal directories and files on the host filesystem. A volume does not increase the size of the containers using it, and the volume\u2019s contents exist outside the lifecycle of a given container.", "We can create a volume using -v option.", "If you want to use the current working directory, use $(pwd).", "Whatever you make changes in the Jupyter notebook, it changes your local file as well.", "You can inspect a docker container:", "It returns the docker object information.", "Let\u2019s install all Python packages when you are creating a container.", "Create a new directory and a file called Dockerfile with the following content:", "We entered in a running container using docker exec and list the Python packages to see if our packages are installed.", "Sign up at hub.docker, then in your terminal:", "The jupyter/scipy-notebook is a Jupyter Notebook scientific Python stack and it includes popular packages from the scientific Python ecosystem. If you want to try Deep Learning then jupyter/tensorfolow-notebook is for you. It includes popular Python deep learning libraries. You can find more images at these links.", "You can use docker not only for the Jupyter Notebook but also for your general development. There are many repositories at the Docker Hub. Try to find official ones you can trust or create your own and push to the Docker Hub. You won\u2019t need to update Python packages on your system anymore.", "Get full access to every story on Medium by becoming a member.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "A programmer and technology enthusiast with a passion for sharing my knowledge and experience."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F